Yummy, fresh tacos, and a decent guac are what you get for the money. Of course it could be way cheaper (e.g. $11 for fresh guac you could get at a grocery for max $5), but this is Brooklyn hipster fare, and all ingredients taste fresh and we'll crafted.

I have ordered from Calexico Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn for many years but I believe they have new staff/employees. When I order take out, it sometimes takes 30 mins. What’s going on? I really love their food but this has happened now  more than one occasion. So sad!
Definitely a unique way to put together a quesadilla. I think that it has some seating area though not much so it brings a cozier environment to the place.

I arrived Calexico at 6:26pm. Put in a take out order. Ordered a Chicken Quesedilla, 2 Chicken Burritos, 2 Chicken Tacos, 1 side of Salsa Verde, and 1 carne Asada Burrito bowl.  The cost was $64. My wait time was 35 minutes.  I noticed one customer who came in after me, got his take out order before me by 10 minutes.  Manager threw in some complimentary guacamole and tortilla chips for free.  It was a busy night.

I swung in here for a quick lunch and ordered the carne asada tacos. I was very pleased with their size and flavor. They have a good variety of hot sauces available, and even little to go packets of Valentina hot sauce (which I appreciated so very much!). The woman behind the counter was very friendly and knowledgeable. I would love to return and try more of the menu.

Food came cold of course and on top of that the chicken was only the breaded part a little piece of avocado for $6 dollars plus tax and service.  Really 6 bucks for a cold tiny taco? Calexico I don't know what's going on with you guys but you guys are doing things not right. Also I've ordered a ground  beef taco that one was ok but also Cold. Another once great restaurant turns greedy. It had been a while since the last time I ate there. In that time Calexico has declined big time. I had to wait 25 minutes for a burrito and rolled quesadilla. The cashier never gave the cook staff the order. Carne asada burrito was full of dry meat, rice and radish. Radish in a burrito?? Quesadilla was also dry and much less cheese then in the past. No more free salsa bar. It now costs $1 for a tiny container of salsa verde. According to my math a jar of their salsa verde would be worth $35. Prices have sky rocketed while quality and service has tanked. Clearly the owners don’t care. Too bad.

No cheese, no salsa, no sour cream, nothing else except rice and some beans!  This shouldn't even be considered Mexican food, it should be in its own category of rice and tortilla!  I would rather drink warm water with salt and mayo and fill my stomach than go pay $13 for a rice wrap!!

Customer service was the worst I've ever experienced. Please save yourself the hassle and avoid this place. They are the ones who overcharged me, yet proceeded to give us a hard time about getting our money back. They messed up our order 4 times and without care or eagerness to fix it. I understand mistakes happen and that is fine but the employees have zero customer service skills and as long as they got their money they didn't care if your order was wrong or you were overcharged. This is unfortunate because I liked this place before this happened. Never again.

While the food quality was great, the service did not welcome my group of 3 regulars to come back. We were overcharged and asked to get a refund or even suggested a gift card for the difference.  The cashiers were unable to do either but also even more unwilling to help come up with a solution until we walked up to the register multiple times to talk through it. Additionally, we did not receive two items for which we paid for until asking and reminding the staff that we ordered them. Lastly, one of our orders was brought out incorrect.  We were made to feel at fault for their mistakes and that is the furthest you can stray from displaying any form of good customer service.

With the exception of Chipotle, I typically don't eat too much Mexican food since I feel the really good ones are few and far between in the city. I'm so glad I decided to give Calexico a try, especially at this particular location where it may be a bit of a walk to get to from the train station, but a great hidden gem that has the no frills local vibe. I got the quesadilla with the crack sauce and now I know why they call it that! BF got a burrito and that was equally as delicious and filling. The guy behind the counter was friendly and even delivered the food to our table. Quality ingredients and tasty food. Muy bueno!
Crack sauce!
Love them, very good NY Mexican. Specials of the day are always good and fresh. Much better than Chipotle on many levels!!
Very good but a little pricey for a burrito spot.
Favorite Mexican in town.  Quesadilla hongos and frozen margaritas.

I used to work in SoHo and eat lunch from the cart every week. Now I live in Brooklyn and make the trip to Columbia Street as often as I can, because Calexico is fodder for serious cravings. I'm crazy about the avocado sauce!
Hip burrito spot with their own 6-point brew.

Best Mexican cuisine in Brooklyn from a former food truck (still eat at their cart in SoHo).  The BBQ pork burrito is to-die for and the grits are tasty. Perhaps the best thing is the pumpkin salsa in the salsa bar.  Not a lot of atmosphere, but the food makes up for it.

Great Mexican restaurant. I went for brunch. We had the rancheros eggs and the burger. Both were super yummy. There is a large extensive menu. Everything was delicious. The staff was very friendly. Prices were extremely reasonable.
Ahhhh.... I don't think you can go wrong with anything on the menu. I love the frijoles burrito with extra crack sauce.
They messed up my order. I clearly asked for carne asada tacos and they gave me chicken. But, then when I tasted it, I almost spit the food out. Not very good.
Some of the best Mexican in the area. Make sure to get the crack sauce on anything you get.
Can I give double smiles for the crack sauce and pumpkin seed salsas.  Rolled carne asada quesadilla is one of my favorite simple Ameri/Mex plates in town.
Perfect burrito neighborhood burrito place.
Not bad though the flavors just don't... meld.

It's a 10 minute jaunt from the nearest train stop, (which is good for burning a few of the calories you're about to consume), but it's totally worth the time!  The food is delicious, they have daily specials, the service is very friendly, and they have a sauce bar, which includes, among other things, an arbol pumpkin seed sauce.  That and the crack sauce make this place a creamy sauce lover's paradise.  The first time I went I had to get the two daily specials tacos: -Rajas: Poblano, bacon, and onion in cream with cotija and cilantro (amazing) -Pulled chicken in spicy pineapple, coconut salsa with pickled onion and cilantro (yummy, but a bit too much chicken)  And that's when I noticed the salsa bar and had to order a small salad in order to be able to utilize it.  And I must say that 4 bucks for the deluxe salad they give you rocks.  This time though I got a couple more things off the menu: -Pulled pork taco (excellent) -Pork grits (so good, served with cheddar, jalapeno, corn and cilantro, mmm)  I will be back again!
